lation in Postcolonial India |first1=Renu |last1=Dube |first2=Reena |last2=Dube |first3=Rashmi |last3=Bhatnagar |journal=Women's Studies Quarterly |volume=27 |issue=1/2 |year=1999 |pages=73\u201386 |jstor=40003400 }}\n* {{cite journal|last=George|first=Sabu M.|title=Female Infanticide in Tamil Nadu, India: From Recognition Back to Denial?|journal=Reproductive Health Matters|year=1997|volume=5|issue=10|pages=124\u2013132|ref= harv|jstor=3775470|doi=10.1016/S0968-8080(97)90093-8}}\n* {{citation |last=Goodkind |first=Daniel |year=1999 |title=Should Prenatal Sex Selection be Restricted?: Ethical Questions and Their Implications for Research and Policy |journal=Population Studies |volume=53 |issue=1 |pages=49\u201361 |doi=10.1080/00324720308069}}\n* {{citation |first=Daniel |last=Grey |date=Fall 2011 |title=Gender, Religion, and Infanticide in Colonial India, 1870\u20131906 |journal=Victorian Review |volume=37 |issue=2 |pages=107\u2013120 |jstor=23646661  |doi=10.1353/vcr.2011.0043}}\n* {{cite book | last=Guilmoto | first=Christophe | title=Sex imbalances at birth : current trends, consequences and policy implications | publisher=UNFPA Asia and the Pacific Regional Office | location=Bangkok, Thailand | year=2012 | isbn=978-974-680-338-0 | ref=harv}}\n* {{citation |first=Marvin |last=Harris |authorlink=Marvin Harris |chapter=Marvin Harris |title=Readings on Human Nature |editor-first=Peter |editor-last=Loptson |publisher=Broadview Press |year=1998 |isbn=978-1-55111-156-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6bGOKpFOY7kC}}\n* {{cite book | last=Hausfater | first=Glenn | title=Infanticide : comparative and evolutionary perspectives | publisher=AldineTransaction | location=New Brunswick, N.J | year=2008 | isbn=978-0-202-36221-2 | ref=harv}}\n* {{citation |title= A Third Explanation for Female Infanticide |first=Kristen |last=Hawkes |journal=Human Ecology |volume=9 |issue=1 |date=March 1981 |pages=79\u201396 |jstor=4602585  |doi=10.1007/bf00887856|pmid=12279255 }}\n* {{citation |last=Hundal |first=Sunny |title=India's 60 million women that never were |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2013/07/201372814110570679.html |accessdate=2015-05-26 |work=Al Jazeera |date=8 August 2013}}\n* {{citation |last=Hvistendahl |first=Mara |authorlink=Mara Hvistendahl |title=Unnatural Selection: Choosing Boys Over Girls, and the Consequences of a World Full of Men |year=2011 |publisher=Public Affairs |isbn=978-1-58648-850-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/unnaturalselecti00mara }}\n* {{citation |last=Jeffery |first=R. |title=Female infanticide and amniocentesis |journal=Social Science & Medicine |year=1984 |volume=19 |issue=11 |pages=1207\u20131212 |pmid=6395348 |last2=Jeffery |first2=P. |last3=Lyon |first3=A. |doi=10.1016/0277-9536(84)90372-1}}\n* {{citation |title=Studying Societies and Cultures: Marvin Harris's Cultural Materialism and Its Legacy |editor1-first=Lawrence A. |editor1-last=Kuznar |editor2-first=Stephen K. |editor2-last=Sanderson |publisher=Paradigm Publishers |year=2007 |isbn=978-1-59451-287-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/studyingsocietie0000unse }}\n* {{cite news|last=Mashru|first=Ram|title=It's a girl: The three deadliest words in the world|url=http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2012/01/16/it%E2%80%99s-a-girl-the-three-deadliest-words-in-the-world/|newspaper=The Independent|date=18 January 2012|ref={{sfnref|Mashru|2012}}|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212082637/http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2012/01/16/it%E2%80%99s-a-girl-the-three-deadliest-words-in-the-world/|archivedate=12 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}\n* {{citation |last=Merry |first=Sally Engle |title=Gender Violence: A Cultural Perspective |year=2008 |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |isbn=978-0-631-22359-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=--z2PP3dFIIC}}\n* {{citation |last=Miller |first=Barbara D. |chapter=Female Infanticide and Child Neglect in Rural India |title=Child Survival: Anthropological Perspectives on the Treatment and Maltreatment of Children |year=1987 |publisher=D. Reidel Publishing |isbn=978-1-55608-028-9 |editor-first=Nancy |editor-last=Scheper-Hughes |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JAz4lv4QLZMC}}\n* {{citation |url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CII2010/cii-2010/Chapter%206.pdf |title=Crimes Against Children |author=National Crime Records Bureau |authorlink=National Crime Records Bureau |year=2010 |accessdate=2015-05-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110085805/http://ncrb.nic.in/CII2010/cii-2010/Chapter%206.pdf |archivedate=10 November 2011 |df=dmy }}\n* {{cite book|last=Oberman|first=Michelle|title=Infanticide Psychosocial and Legal Perspectives on Mothers Who Kill|year=2005|publisher=American Psychiatric Publishing|isbn=1-58562-097-1|edition=1st|editor=Margaret G. Spinelli|chapter=A Brief History of Infanticide and the Law|ref= harv}}\n* {{citation |last1=Parrot |first1=Andrea |last2=Cummings |first2=Andrea |title=Forsaken Females: The Global Brutalization of Women |year=2006 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-0-7425-4579-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_d_A5kcaKAAC}}\n* {{cite book|last=Perwez|first=Shahid|title=Civilizing Missions in Colonial and Postcolonial South Asia: From Improvement to Development|year=2011|publisher=Anthem Press|isbn=978-1-84331-864-4|pages=243\u2013316|editor=Carey Anthony Watt |editor2=Michael Mann|chapter=Female Infanticide and the Civilizing Mission in Post Colonial India: A Case Study from Tamil Nadu c. 1980\u20132006|ref= harv}}\n* {{citation |first=Sheetal |last=Ranjan |chapter=Crimes Against Women in India |editor-first=N. Prabha |editor-last=Unnithan |title=Crime and Justice in India |year=2013 |publisher=SAGE Publications |isbn=978-8-13210-977-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k_6HAwAAQBAJ}}\n* {{citation |first=Elaine |last=Rose |year=1999 |title=Consumption smoothing and excess female mortality in rural India |journal=The Review of Economics and Statistics |volume=81 |issue=1 |pages=41\u201349 |jstor=2646784  |doi=10.1162/003465399767923809}}\n* {{citation |last=Scott |first=Eleanor |editor1-last=Arnold |editor1-first=Bettina |editor2-last=Wicker |editor2-first=Nancy L. |title=Gender and the Archaeology of Death |year=2001 |publisher=AltaMira Press |isbn=978-0-7591-0137-1 |chapter=Killing the Female? Archaeological Narratives of Infanticide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6hVz6RzCkJcC}}\n* {{citation |last=Snehi |first=Yogesh |title=Female Infanticide and Gender in Punjab: Imperial Claims and Contemporary Discourse |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=38 |issue=41 |date=11 October 2003 |pages=4302\u20134305 |jstor=4414126 }}\n* {{citation|last1=Visaria|first1=Leela|title=The Cambridge Economic History of India|year=1983|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-22802-2|edition=Volume 2|first2=Pravin |last2=Visaria |first3=Sardar |last3=Patel|editor=[[Tapan Raychaudhuri]] |editor2=Irfan Habib |editor3=Dharma Kumar|chapter=Population (1757\u20131947)|ref= harv}}\n*{{citation |last=Vishwanath |first=L. S.|title=Sex-Selective Abortion in India: Gender, Society and New Reproductive Technologies |year=2007 |publisher=SAGE |isbn=978-0-76193-539-1 |editor-first=Tulsi |editor-last=Patel |chapter=Female Infanticide, Property and the Colonial State |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UegqZBISwBYC}}\n* {{cite book|last=Winkler|first=Theodor H.|title=Women in an Insecure World|year=2005|publisher=Geneva Centre for the Democratic Control of Armed Forces|chapter-url=http://www.unicef.org/emerg/files/women_insecure_world.pdf|chapter=Slaughtering Eve The Hidden Gendercide|ref= harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |last1=Barlow |first1=Sally H. |last2=Clayton |first2=Claudia J. |editor-last=Hall |editor-first=Harold V. |title=Lethal Violence: A Sourcebook on Fatal Domestic, Acquaintance and Stranger Violence |year=1998 |publisher=CRC Press |isbn=978-0-8493-7003-8 |chapter=When Mothers Murder: Understanding Infanticide by Females |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9KXJoS2pQJMC}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Bhatnagar |first1=Rashmi Dube |first2=Renu |last2=Dube |first3=Reena |last3=Dube |title=Female Infanticide in India: A Feminist Cultural History |year=2005 |publisher=State University of New York Press |isbn=978-0-7914-6327-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kT0s8TXoffsC}}\n* {{cite news |last=Bunting |first=Madeleine |authorlink=Madeleine Bunting |title=India's missing women |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/poverty-matters/2011/jul/22/india-sex-selection-missing-women|accessdate=2015-05-26 |work=The Guardian |date=22 July 2011}}\n*[[Shilpi Somaya Gowda|Gowda, Shilpi]] (2010): ''Secret Daughter''\n*{{cite book |last=Kannabiran |first=Kalpana |title=Writings on Human Rights, Law and Society in India: Combat Law Anthology 2002\u20132010 |year=2011 |publisher=Human Rights Law Network, India (Socio-Legal Information Centre) |isbn=978-81-89479-78-7 |editor-first=Harsh |editor-last=Dobhal |chapter=Gender Cleansing |quote=Female Foeticide and female infanticide satisfy four of the five criteria set out in the Genocide Convention |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CcbLvuT1jbkC}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Meyer |first1=Cheryl L. |last2=Oberman |first2=Michelle |title=Mothers Who Kill Their Children: Inside the Minds of Moms from Susan Smith to the \"Prom Mom\" |year=2001 |publisher=New York University Press |isbn=978-0-8147-5643-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0g6xYkMUrKkC}}\n* {{cite news|last=Krishnan|first=Murali|title=Female infanticide in India mocks claims of progress|url=http://www.dw.de/female-infanticide-in-india-mocks-claims-of-progress/a-15900828|newspaper=Deutsche Welle|date=20 March 2012|editor=Shamil Shams}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Nelson |first1=Dean |title=India 'most dangerous place in world to be born a girl' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/india/9054429/India-most-dangerous-place-in-world-to-be-born-a-girl.html |accessdate=2015-05-26 |publisher=The Daily Telegraph |date=1 February 2012}}\n* {{cite book |first=Brian K. |last=Pennington |year=2005 |url=https://www.questia.com/read/120211438/was-hinduism-invented-britons-indians-and-colonial |title=Was Hinduism Invented?: Britons, Indians, and the Colonial Construction |publisher=Oxford University Press |via=[[Questia]] |url-access=subscription }}\n* {{cite book |last=Ramachandran |first=Nira |title=Persisting Undernutrition in India: Causes, Consequences and Possible Solutions |publisher=Springer |year=2014 | isbn=978-8-13221-831-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lvH2ngEACAAJ}}\n* {{cite book |last=Sadhak |first=H. |title=Pension Reform in India: The Unfinished Agenda |publisher=Sage Publications |year=2013 |isbn= 978-8-13211-649-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qN2GAwAAQBAJ}}\n*{{cite book | last=Smith | first=M | title=Homicide : a sourcebook of social research | publisher=Sage Publications | location=Thousand Oaks, Calif | year=1999 | isbn=978-0-7619-0765-7}}\n\n{{Social issues in India}}\n\n[[Category:Sex selection in India| ]]\n[[Category:Child abandonment]]\n[[Category:Infanticide|India]]\n[[Category:Childhood in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Violence against women}}\n\n'''Female infanticide in India''' has a history spanning centuries. [[Poverty in India|Poverty]], the [[Dowry system in India|dowry system]], births to unmarried women, deformed infants, famine, lack of support services and maternal illnesses such as [[postpartum depression]] are among the causes that have been proposed to explain the phenomenon of [[female infanticide]] in India.\n\nAlthough infanticide has been criminalised in India, it remains an under-reported crime due to the lack of reliable data. In 2010, the [[National Crime Records Bureau]] reported approximately 100 male and female infanticides, producing an official rate of less than one case of infanticide per million people.\n\nThe Indian practice of female infanticide and of [[sex-selective abortion]] have been cited to explain in part a gender imbalance that has been reported as being increasingly distorted since the [[1991 Census of India]], although there are also other influences that might affect the trend.{{sfnp|Hundal|2013|ps=}}\n\n== Definition ==\nSection 315 of the [[Indian Penal Code]] defines infanticide as the killing of an infant in the 0\u20131 year age group. The Code uses this definition to differentiate between infanticide and numerous other crimes against children, such as [[Female foeticide in India|foeticide]] and [[murder]].{{sfnp|National Crime Records Bureau|2010|p=1|ps=}}{{efn|According to statistics published by the [[National Crime Records Bureau]], a department of the [[Government of India]], kidnapping and abduction represented 40.3 per cent of recorded crimes against children in 2010, rape was 20.5 per cent, murder (other than infanticide) was 5.3 per cent, and exposure and abandonment was 2.7 per cent. All other crimes against children accounted for 31.5 per cent.{{sfnp|National Crime Records Bureau|2010|p=6|ps=}}}}\n\nSome scholarly publications on infanticide use the legal definition.{{sfnp|Craig|2004|ps=: referring to the United Kingdom [[Infanticide Act 1938]].}}{{sfnp|Miller|1987|p=97|ps=: \"Most broadly defined, infanticide applies to the killing of children under the age of twelve months (deaths after that age would generally be classified as child ''homicide'', although the definition and, hence, duration of childhood is culturally variable).\" }} Others, such as the collaboration of Renu Dube, Reena Dube and Rashmi Bhatnagar, who describe themselves as \"postcolonial feminists\", adopt a broader scope for ''infanticide'', applying it from foeticide through to [[femicide]] at an unspecified age.{{sfnp|Dube|Dube|Bhatnagar|1999|p=74|ps=}} Barbara Miller, an anthropologist, has \"for convenience\"  used the term to refer to all non-accidental deaths of children up to the age of around 15\u201316, which is culturally considered to be the age when childhood ends in rural India. She notes that the act of infanticide can be \"outright\", such as a physical beating, or take a \"passive\" form through actions such as neglect and starvation. [[Neonaticide]], being the killing of a child within 24 hours of birth, is sometimes considered as a separate study.{{sfnp|Miller|1987|pp=96-97|ps=}}\n\n== Colonial period ==\n\n=== Causation ===\nBritish colonists in India first became aware of the practice of female infanticide in 1789, during the period of [[Company Rule in India|Company Rule]]. It was noted among members of a [[Rajput]] clan by [[Jonathan Duncan (Governor of Bombay)|Jonathan Duncan]], then the [[British Resident]] in [[Jaunpur district]] of what is now the northern [[States and union territories of India|state]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]]. Later, in 1817, officials noted that the practice was so entrenched that there were entire [[taluk]]s of the [[Jadeja]] Rajputs in [[Gujarat]] where no female children of the clan existed.{{sfnp|Vishwanath|2007|p=270|ps=}} In the mid-19th century, a magistrate who was stationed in the north-west of the country claimed that for several hundred years no daughter had ever been raised in the strongholds of the Rajahs of [[Mainpuri district|Mynpoorie]] and that only after the intervention of a [[District Collector]] in 1845 did the Rajput ruler there keep a daughter alive.{{sfnp|Miller|1987|pp=97\u201398|ps=}} The British identified other [[Caste in India|high-caste]] communities as practitioners in north, western and central areas of the country; these included the [[Ahir]]s, [[Bedi clan|Bedis]], [[Gurjar]]s, [[Jat people|Jats]], [[Khatri]]s, [[Kanbi|Lewa Kanbis]], [[Mohyal]] Brahmins and [[Patidar]]s.{{sfnp|Vishwanath|2007|p=270|ps=}}{{sfnp|Snehi|2003|ps=}}\n\nAccording to [[Marvin Harris]], another anthropologist and among the first proponents of [[Cultural materialism (anthropology)|cultural materialism]], these killings of legitimate children occurred only among the Rajputs and other elite land-owning and warrior groups. The rationale was mainly economic, lying in a desire not to split land and wealth among too many heirs and in avoiding the payment of dowries. Sisters and daughters would marry men of similar standing and thus pose a challenge to the cohesion of wealth and power, whereas concubines and their children would not and thus could be allowed to live.{{sfnp|Scott|2001|pp=6-7|ps=: Citing {{cite book |title=Our Kind: Who We Are, Where We Came From, Where We Are Going |first=Marvin |last=Harris |authorlink=Marvin Harris |publisher=Harper & Row |year=1989 |isbn= |pages=213, 226\u2013227}}}}{{sfnp|Harris|1998|p=558|ps=}} He further argues that the need for warriors in the villages of a pre-industrial society meant female children were devalued, and the combination of war casualties and infanticide acted as a necessary form of population control.{{sfnp|Hawkes|1981|ps=}}\n\n[[Sociobiology|Sociobiologists]] have a different theory to Harris. Indeed, his theory and interest in the topic of infanticide is born of his more generalised opposition to the sociobiological hypothesis of the procreative imperative.{{sfnp|Scott|2001|p=6|ps=}}{{sfnp|Kuznar|Sanderson|2007|p=209|ps=}} According to this theory of imperative, based on the 19th-century vogue for explanations rooted in evolution and its premise of natural selection,{{sfnp|Scott|2001|pp=3-4|ps=}} the biological differences between men and women meant that many more children could be gained among the elites through support for male offspring, whose fecundity was naturally much greater: the line would spread and grow more extensively. Harris believes this to be a fallacious explanation because the elites had sufficient wealth easily to support both male and female children.{{sfnp|Harris|1998|p=558|ps=}} Thus, Harris and others, such as [[William Divale]], see female infanticide as a way to restrict population growth, while sociobiologists such as [[Mildred Dickemann]] view the same practice as a means of expanding it.{{sfnp|Hawkes|1981|ps=}}\n\nAnother anthropologist, [[Kristen Hawkes]], has criticised both of these theories. On the one hand, opposing Harris, she says both that the quickest way to get more male warriors would have been to have more females as child-bearers and that having more females in a village would increase the potential for marriage alliances with other villages. Against the procreative imperative theory she points out that the corollary to well-off elites such as those in northern India wanting to maximise reproduction is that poor people would want to minimise it and thus in theory should have practiced male infanticide, which it seems they did not.{{sfnp|Hawkes|1981|ps=}}\n\n=== Reliability of colonial reports on infanticide ===\n\nThere is no data for the [[human sex ratio|sex ratio]] in India prior to the British colonial era. Reliant as the British were on local high-caste communities for the collection of taxes and the maintenance of law and order, the administrators were initially reluctant to peer too deeply into their private affairs, such as the practice of infanticide. Although this did change in the 1830s, the reluctance reappeared following the cathartic events of the [[Indian rebellion of 1857]], which caused government by the [[East India Company]] to be supplanted by the [[British Raj]].{{sfnp|Vishwanath|2007|pp=268-269|ps=}} In 1857, John Cave Browne, a chaplain serving in [[Bengal Presidency]], reported a Major Goldney speculating that the practice of female infanticide among the Jats in the [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab Province]] originated from \"Malthusian motives\".{{sfnp|Browne|1857|pp=121\u2013122|ps=}} In the Gujarat region, the first cited examples of discrepancies in the sex ratio among Lewa Patidars and [[Kunbi|Kanbis]] dates from 1847.{{sfnp|Vishwanath|2007|p=278|ps=}} These historical records have been questioned by modern scholars. The British made their observations from a distance and never mixed with their Indian subjects to understand their poverty, frustrations, life or culture at close hand.{{sfnp|Cohn|1996|p=10|ps=}} Browne documented his speculations on female infanticide using \"they tell\" hearsay.{{sfnp|Browne|1857|pp=121\u2013122|ps=}} [[Bernard Cohn (anthropologist)|Bernard Cohn]] states that the colonial British residents in India would not accuse an individual or family of infanticide as the crime was difficult to prove in a British court, nevertheless accused an entire clan or social group of female infanticide. Cohn says, \"female infanticide thus became a 'statistical crime'\", during the colonial rule of India.{{sfnp|Cohn|1996|pp=10-11|ps=}}\n\nAside from numerous reports and correspondence on infanticide from colonial officials,{{sfnp|Snehi|2003|ps=}} there was also documentation from Christian missionaries. who were significant writers of ethnographies of India during the 19th century. They sent letters back to Britain announcing their missionary accomplishments and characterising the culture as savage, ignorant and depraved.{{sfnp|Grey|2011|ps=}}{{sfnp|Dirks|2001|pp=173-174|ps=}} Scholars have questioned this distorted construction of Indian culture during the colonial era, stating that infanticide was as common in England during the 18th and 19th century, as in India.{{sfnp|Grey|2011|ps=}}<ref name=\"anagol\">{{cite journal |first=Padma |last=Anagol |authorlink = Padma Anagol |title=The Emergence of the Female Criminal in India: Infanticide and Survival under the Raj |journal=History Workshop Journal |issue=53 |date=Spring 2002 |pages=73\u201393 |jstor=4289774 }}</ref><ref>GA Oddie (1994), Orientalism and British [[Protestant]] missionary constructions of India in the nineteenth century, Journal of South Asian Studies, 17(2), pp. 27\u201342</ref> Some British Christian missionaries of the late 19th century, states Daniel Grey, wrongly believed that female infanticide was sanctioned by the scriptures of Hinduism and Islam, and against which Christianity had \"centuries after centuries come into victorious conflict\".{{sfnp|Grey|2011|ps=}}\n\n=== Location and direct method ===\n\n[[File:6th Earl of Mayo.jpg|thumb|[[Richard Bourke, 6th Earl of Mayo]], who was [[Governor-General of India]] at the time of the [[Female Infanticide Prevention Act, 1870]].]]\n\nA review of scholarship by Miller has shown that the majority of female infanticides in India during the colonial period occurred in the north-west, and that it was widespread although not all groups carried out this practice.{{sfnp|Miller|1987|p=99|ps=}}\n\n[[David Arnold (historian)|David Arnold]], a member of the [[Subaltern studies|subaltern studies group]] who has used a lot of contemporary sources, says that various methods of outright infanticide were used, including reputedly including poisoning with [[opium]], strangulation and suffocation. Poisonous substances such as the root of the ''[[plumbago rosea]]'' and [[arsenic]] were used for abortion, with the latter also ironically being used as an [[aphrodisiac]] and cure for [[male impotence]]. The act of direct infanticide among Rajputs was usually performed by women, often the mother herself or a nurse. Administration of poison was in any event a type of killing particularly associated with women; Arnold describes it as \"often murder by proxy\", with the man at a remove from the event and thus able to claim innocence.{{sfnp|Arnold|2013|pp=176, 179|ps=}}\n\nThe passing of the [[Female Infanticide Prevention Act, 1870]] made the practice illegal in the [[British India]]n regions of Punjab and the [[North-Western Provinces]].{{sfnp|Miller|1987|p=99|ps=}} The [[Governor-General of India]] had the authority to expand the Act to other regions at his discretion.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\n=== Impact of famines on infanticide ===\n\nMajor [[Famine in India|famines occurred in India]] every five to eight years in the 19th- and early 20th-centuries,<ref>B Murton (2000), Famine, in The Cambridge World History of Food 2, pp. 1411\u20131427, Cambridge University Press</ref><ref>Mike Davis (2001), Late Victorian Holocausts: El Ni\u00f1o Famines and the Making of the Third World, pp. 7\u20138, Verso</ref> resulting in millions starving to death.<ref>Mike Davis (2004), Liberation Ecologies: Environment, Development and Social Movements, pp. 44\u201349, Routledge</ref><ref>A Sen (1983), Poverty and Famines: An Essay on Entitlement and Deprivation, Oxford University Press</ref> As also happened in China, these events begat infanticide: desperate starving parents would either kill a suffering infant, sell a child to buy food for the rest of the family, or beg people to take them away for nothing and feed them.<ref name=cog1>Cormac \u00d3 Gr\u00e1da, Famine: A Short History, pp. 61\u201367, Princeton University Press</ref><ref>William Digby, The Famine Campaign in Southern India (Madras and Bombay): 1876\u20131878, pp. 458\u2013459, Longmans London</ref><ref name=gupshu1>Gupta and Shuzhuo, Gender Bias in China, South Korea and India 1920\u20131990: Effects of War, Famine and Fertility Decline, Development and Change, Volume 30, Issue 3, pp. 619\u2013652, July 1999</ref> Gupta and Shuzhou state that massive famines and poverty-related historical events had influenced historical sex ratios, and they have had deep cultural ramifications on girls and regional attitudes towards female [[infant mortality]].<ref name=gupshu1 />\n\n=== Impact of economic policies on infanticide ===\n\nAccording to [[Mara Hvistendahl]], documents left behind by the colonial administration following [[Partition of India|independence]] showed a direct correlation between the taxation policies of the [[British East India Company]] and the rise in female infanticide.{{sfnp|Hvistendahl|2011|p=67|ps=}}\n\n=== Regional and religious demographics ===\n\nThe [[Census of India prior to independence|decennial census of India]] from 1881 through 1941 recorded a consistently skewed ratio whereby the number of males exceeded the number of females. The gender difference was particularly high in north and western regions of India, with an overall sex ratio&nbsp;\u2013 males per 100 females&nbsp;\u2013 of between 110.2 and 113.7 in the north over the 60-year period, and 105.8 to 109.8 males for every 100 female in western India for all ages. Visaria states that female deficit among Muslims was markedly higher, next only to Sikhs. South India region was an exception reporting excess females overall, which scholars attribute partly to selective emigration of males and the regional practice of matriarchy.{{sfn|Visaria|Visaria|Patel|1983|pp=496-499}}\n\nThe overall sex ratios, and excess males, in various regions were highest among the [[Islam in India|Muslim population of India]] from 1881 to 1941, and the sex ratio of each region correlated with the proportion of its Muslim population, with the exception of eastern region of India where the overall sex ratio was relatively low while it had a high percentage of Muslims in the population.{{sfn|Visaria|Visaria|Patel|1983|p=499 with footnote 2}} If regions that are now part of modern Pakistan are excluded (Baluchistan, North West Frontier, Sind for example), Visaria states that the regional and overall sex ratios for the rest of India over the 1881\u20131941 period improve in favour of females, with a lesser gap between male and female population.{{sfn|Visaria|Visaria|Patel|1983|p=499 with footnote 1}}\n\n== Contemporary data and statistics ==\n\nInfanticide in India, and elsewhere in the world, is a difficult issue to objectively access because reliable data is unavailable.{{sfn | Hausfater | 2008 | pp=445\u2013450 (Susan Scrimshaw)}}<ref>John Cole, Geography of the World\u2019s major regions (1996), Routledge, p. 14, {{ISBN|978-0-415-11742-5}}</ref> Scrimshaw states that not only accurate frequency of female infanticide is unknown, differential care between male and female infants is even more elusive data.{{sfn | Hausfater | 2008 | pp=445\u2013450 (Susan Scrimshaw)}} Reliable data for female infanticide is unavailable. Its frequency, and that of sex-selective abortion, is indirectly estimated from the observed high birth sex ratio; that is, the ratio of boys to girls at birth or 0\u20131 age group infants, or 0\u20136 age group child sex ratio.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Gene-culture coevolution and sex ratios: the effects of infanticide, sex-selective abortion, sex selection, and sex-biased parental investment on the evolution of sex ratios |last1=Kumm |first1=J. |last2=Laland |first2=K. N. |last3=Feldman |first3=M. W. |pmid=7846643 |journal=Theoretical Population Biology |date=December 1994 |volume= 46|pages=249\u2013278 |doi=10.1006/tpbi.1994.1027 |issue=3; number 3}}</ref> The natural ratio is assumed to be 106, or somewhere between 103 and 107, and any number above or below this range is considered as suggestive of female or male foeticide respectively.<ref>Therese Hesketh and Zhu Wei Xing, Abnormal sex ratios in human populations: Causes and consequences, PNAS, 5 September 2006, vol. 103, no. 36, pp 13271-13275</ref><ref name=whj8>{{cite journal|author=James W.H.|title=Hypothesis:Evidence that Mammalian Sex Ratios at birth are partially controlled by parental hormonal levels around the time of conception|journal=Journal of Endocrinology|volume=198|pages=3\u201315|date=July 2008|doi= 10.1677/JOE-07-0446|issue=1|pmid=18577567}}</ref>\n\nHigher sex ratios than in India have been reported for the last 20 years in China, Pakistan, Vietnam, Azerbaijan, Armenia, Georgia and some Southeast European countries, and attributed in part to female infanticide, among other factors.{{sfn | Guilmoto | 2012 | pp=15\u201328}} There is an ongoing debate as to the cause of high sex ratios in the 0\u20131 and 0\u20136 age groups in India. The suggested reasons for high birth sex ratio include regional female foeticide using [[amniocentesis]] regardless of income or poverty because of patrilineal culture,{{sfnp|Jeffery|Jeffery|Lyon|1984|ps=}}{{sfnp|Goodkind|1999|ps=}} the under-reporting of female births,<ref>Bonnie Smith, The Oxford Encyclopedia of Women in World History, p. 354, Oxford University Press (2008), {{ISBN|978-0195148909}}</ref> smaller family size and selective stopping of family size once a male is born.<ref>Shelley Clark, Son preference and sex composition of children: Evidence from India, Demography, February 2000, Volume 37, Issue 1, pp 95\u2013108</ref><ref>Perwez & Jeffrey, Declining Child Sex Ratioand Sex-Selection in India \u2013 A Demographic Epiphany?, E&P Weekly, 18 August 2012, Vol. XLVII, No. 33, pp. 73\u201377</ref>\n\nSheetal Ranjan reports that the total male and female infanticide reported cases in India were 139 in 1995, 86 in 2005 and 111 in 2010;{{sfnp|Ranjan|2013|p=257|ps=}} the National Crime Records Bureau summary for 2010 gives a figure of 100.{{sfnp|National Crime Records Bureau|2010|p=95|ps=}} Scholars state that infanticide is an under-reported crime.<ref name=mspi1>M Spinelli (2002), Infanticide: contrasting views, Archives of Women\u2019s Mental Health, 8(1), pp. 15\u201324</ref>\n\nReports of regional cases of female infanticide have appeared in the media, such as those in [[Usilampatti]] in southern Tamil Nadu.{{sfn|George|1997|pp=124\u2013132}}\n\nOne of the biggest reason for increase in female infanticide is being associated with the increase in number of private Ultrasound Scanning Centres which often tell the sex of baby, and as they become more accessible and affordable people who could not find out the sex of baby historically, have started finding it out and often results in abortion in case of girl child.\n\n== Reasons ==\n\nExtreme poverty with an inability to afford raising a child is one of the reasons given for female infanticide in India.<ref name=rg1>{{cite journal | last1 = Giriraj | first1 = R. | year = 2004 | title = Changing Attitude to Female Infanticide in Salem | url = | journal = Journal of Social Welfare | volume = 50 | issue = 11| pages = 13\u201314 & 34\u201335 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Tandon | first1 = Sl | last2 = Sharma | first2 = R | year = 2006 | title = Female Foeticide and Infanticide in India: An Analysis of Crimes against Girl Children | url = | journal = International Journal of Criminal Justice Sciences | volume = 1 | issue = 1| pages = 1\u20137 }}</ref>{{clarify|reason=this might be a reason for infanticide but we need to explain why it is a reason for gender-specific infanticide|date=May 2015}} Such poverty has been a major reason for high infanticide rates in various cultures, throughout history, including England, France and India.<ref name=\"anagol\"/><ref name=\"R Sauer 1978 pp. 81-93\">{{cite journal | last1 = Sauer | first1 = R | year = 1978 | title = Infanticide and abortion in nineteenth-century Britain | url = | journal = Population Studies | volume = 32 | issue = 1| pages = 81\u201393 | doi=10.2307/2173842| pmid = 11630571 | jstor = 2173842 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Kellum | first1 = B.A. | year = 1974 | title = Infanticide in England in the later Middle Ages | url = | journal = History of Childhood Quarterly | volume = 1 | issue = 3| pages = 367\u201388 | pmid = 11614565 }}</ref>\n\nThe dowry system in India is another reason that is given for female infanticide. Although India has taken steps to abolish the dowry system,{{sfnp|Parrot|Cummings|2006|p=160|ps=}} the practice persists, and for poorer families in rural regions female infanticide and gender selective abortion is attributed to the fear of being unable to raise a suitable dowry and then being socially ostracised.{{sfn|Oberman|2005|pp=5\u20136}}\n\nOther major reasons given for infanticide, both female and male, include unwanted children, such as those conceived after rape, deformed children born to impoverished families, and those born to unmarried mothers lacking reliable, safe and affordable birth control.<ref name=rg1 /><ref>Christine Alder and Ken Polk, Child Victims of Homicide, Cambridge University Press, p. 4-5, {{ISBN|978-0-521-00251-6}}</ref>{{sfn | Hausfater | 2008 | pp=445\u2013450 (Susan Scrimshaw)}} Relationship difficulties, low income, lack of support coupled with mental illness such as [[postpartum depression]] have also been reported as reasons for female infanticide in India.<ref name=cha1>Chandran et al (2002), Post-partum depression in a cohort of women from a rural area of Tamil Nadu, India: Incidence and risk factors, The British Journal of Psychiatry, 181(6), pp. 499\u2013504</ref><ref>Chandra et al, Infanticidal ideas and infanticidal behavior in Indian women with severe postpartum psychiatric disorders, J Nerv Ment Dis. 2002 Jul 190(7), pp. 457\u201361</ref><ref>{{Citation|pages=37\u2013141|pmc=2174580|pmid=18188430|year=2007|last1=Hatters Friedman|first1=S|title=Child murder by mothers: Patterns and prevention|journal=World Psychiatry |volume=6|issue=3|last2=Resnick|first2=P. J.}}</ref>{{clarify|reason=this might be a reason for infanticide but we need to explain why it is a reason for gender-specific infanticide|date=May 2015}}\n\nElaine Rose in 1999 reported that disproportionately high female mortality is correlated to poverty, infrastructure and means to feed one's family, and that there has been an increase in the ratio of the probability that a girl survives to the probability that a boy survives with favourable rainfall each year and the consequent ability to irrigate farms in rural India.{{sfnp|Rose|1999|ps=}}\n\nIan Darnton-Hill et al. state that the effect of malnutrition, particularly micronutrient and vitamin deficiency, depends on sex, and it adversely impacts female infant mortality.<ref>Ian Darnton-Hill, Patrick Webb, Philip WJ Harvey, Joseph M Hunt, Nita Dalmiya, Mickey Chopra, Madeleine J Ball, Martin W Bloem and Bruno de Benoist, Micronutrient deficiencies and gender: social and economic costs, American Journal of Clinical Nutrition, May 2005, vol. 81, no. 5, pp. 1198S-1205S</ref>\n\n== State response ==\nIn 1991 the [[Girl Child Protection Scheme]] was launched. This operates as a long-term financial incentive, with rural families having to meet certain obligations such as sterilisation of the mother. Once the obligations are met, the state puts aside {{INR}}2000 in a state-run fund. The fund, which should grow to {{INR}}10,000, is released to the daughter when she is 20: she can use it either to marry or to pursue higher education.{{sfnp|Perwez|2011|p=250-251|ps=}}\n\nIn 1992 the [[Government of India]] started the \"baby cradle scheme\". This allows families anonymously to give their child up for adoption without having to go through the formal procedure. The scheme has been praised for possibly saving the lives of thousands of baby girls but also criticised by human rights groups, who say that the scheme encourages child abandonment and also reinforces the low status in which women are held.{{sfnp|Bhalla|2012|ps=}} The scheme, which was piloted in [[Tamil Nadu]], saw cradles placed outside state-operated health facilities. The [[Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu]] added another incentive, giving money to families that had more than one daughter. 136 baby girls were given for adoption during the first four years of the scheme. In 2000, 1,218 cases of female infanticide were reported, the scheme was deemed a failure and it was abandoned. It was reinstated in the following year.{{sfnp|Parrot|Cummings|2006|pp=64\u201365|ps=}}\n\nThe 2011 census data showed a significant decline in the child sex ratio (CSR). Alarmed by the decline, the Government of India introduced [[Beti Bachao, Beti Padhao]] (BBBP) initiative. The program is intended to prevent gender discrimination and to ensure survival, protection and education of girls.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/beti-bachao-beti-padhao-programme-extended-to-all-640-districts-to-improve-child-sex-ratio/articleshow/61759269.cms|title='Beti Bachao Beti Padhao' programme extended to all 640 districts to improve child sex ratio - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-01-29}}</ref>\n\n== International reactions ==\n\nThe [[Geneva Centre for the Democratic Control of Armed Forces]] (DCAF) wrote in their 2005 report, ''Women in an Insecure World'', that at a time when the number of casualties in war had fallen, a \"secret genocide\" was being carried out against women.{{sfn|Mashru|2012}} According to DCAF the demographic shortfall of women who have died for gender related issues is in the same range as the 191 million estimated dead from all conflicts in the 20th century.{{sfnp|Winkler|2005|p=7|ps=}} In 2012, the documentary ''[[It's a Girl: The Three Deadliest Words in the World]]'' was released. This focused on [[female infanticide in China]] and in India.{{sfnp|DeLugan|2013|pp=649\u2013650|ps=}}\n\nIn 1991 [[Elisabeth Bumiller]] wrote ''May You be the Mother of a Hundred Sons: A Journey Among the Women of India'' around the subject of infanticide.{{sfn|Bumiller|1998|p=1}} In the chapter on female infanticide, titled ''No More Little Girls'', she said that the prevailing reason for the practice is \"not as the act of monsters in a barbarian society but as the last resort of impoverished, uneducated women driven to do what they thought was best for themselves and their families.\"{{sfnp|Dehejia|1990|ps=}}\n\n''Gift of A Girl Female Infanticide'' is a 1998 documentary that explores the prevalence of female infanticide in southern India, as well as steps which have been taken to help eradicate the practice. The documentary won an award from the [[Association for Asian Studies]].{{sfnp|Al-Malazi|1998|ps=}}{{sfnp|Merry|2008|ps=}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Sati (practice)|Sati]]\n* [[Kuri Mar]]\n* [[Female foeticide in India]]\n\n== References ==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n'''Citatio