l Materialism and Its Legacy |editor1-first=Lawrence A. |editor1-last=Kuznar |editor2-first=Stephen K. |editor2-last=Sanderson |publisher=Paradigm Publishers |year=2007 |isbn=978-1-59451-287-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/studyingsocietie0000unse }}\n* {{cite news|last=Mashru|first=Ram|title=It's a girl: The three deadliest words in the world|url=http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2012/01/16/it%E2%80%99s-a-girl-the-three-deadliest-words-in-the-world/|newspaper=The Independent|date=18 January 2012|ref={{sfnref|Mashru|2012}}|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212082637/http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2012/01/16/it%E2%80%99s-a-girl-the-three-deadliest-words-in-the-world/|archivedate=12 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}\n* {{citation |last=Merry |first=Sally Engle |title=Gender Violence: A Cultural Perspective |year=2008 |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |isbn=978-0-631-22359-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=--z2PP3dFIIC}}\n* {{citation |last=Miller |first=Barbara D. |chapter=Female Infanticide and Child Neglect in Rural India |title=Child Survival: Anthropological Perspectives on the Treatment and Maltreatment of Children |year=1987 |publisher=D. Reidel Publishing |isbn=978-1-55608-028-9 |editor-first=Nancy |editor-last=Scheper-Hughes |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JAz4lv4QLZMC}}\n* {{citation |url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CII2010/cii-2010/Chapter%206.pdf |title=Crimes Against Children |author=National Crime Records Bureau |authorlink=National Crime Records Bureau |year=2010 |accessdate=2015-05-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110085805/http://ncrb.nic.in/CII2010/cii-2010/Chapter%206.pdf |archivedate=10 November 2011 |df=dmy }}\n* {{cite book|last=Oberman|first=Michelle|title=Infanticide Psychosocial and Legal Perspectives on Mothers Who Kill|year=2005|publisher=American Psychiatric Publishing|isbn=1-58562-097-1|edition=1st|editor=Margaret G. Spinelli|chapter=A Brief History of Infanticide and the Law|ref= harv}}\n* {{citation |last1=Parrot |first1=Andrea |last2=Cummings |first2=Andrea |title=Forsaken Females: The Global Brutalization of Women |year=2006 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-0-7425-4579-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_d_A5kcaKAAC}}\n* {{cite book|last=Perwez|first=Shahid|title=Civilizing Missions in Colonial and Postcolonial South Asia: From Improvement to Development|year=2011|publisher=Anthem Press|isbn=978-1-84331-864-4|pages=243\u2013316|editor=Carey Anthony Watt |editor2=Michael Mann|chapter=Female Infanticide and the Civilizing Mission in Post Colonial India: A Case Study from Tamil Nadu c. 1980\u20132006|ref= harv}}\n* {{citation |first=Sheetal |last=Ranjan |chapter=Crimes Against Women in India |editor-first=N. Prabha |editor-last=Unnithan |title=Crime and Justice in India |year=2013 |publisher=SAGE Publications |isbn=978-8-13210-977-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k_6HAwAAQBAJ}}\n* {{citation |first=Elaine |last=Rose |year=1999 |title=Consumption smoothing and excess female mortality in rural India |journal=The Review of Economics and Statistics |volume=81 |issue=1 |pages=41\u201349 |jstor=2646784  |doi=10.1162/003465399767923809}}\n* {{citation |last=Scott |first=Eleanor |editor1-last=Arnold |editor1-first=Bettina |editor2-last=Wicker |editor2-first=Nancy L. |title=Gender and the Archaeology of Death |year=2001 |publisher=AltaMira Press |isbn=978-0-7591-0137-1 |chapter=Killing the Female? Archaeological Narratives of Infanticide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6hVz6RzCkJcC}}\n* {{citation |last=Snehi |first=Yogesh |title=Female Infanticide and Gender in Punjab: Imperial Claims and Contemporary Discourse |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=38 |issue=41 |date=11 October 2003 |pages=4302\u20134305 |jstor=4414126 }}\n* {{citation|last1=Visaria|first1=Leela|title=The Cambridge Economic History of India|year=1983|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-22802-2|edition=Volume 2|first2=Pravin |last2=Visaria |first3=Sardar |last3=Patel|editor=[[Tapan Raychaudhuri]] |editor2=Irfan Habib |editor3=Dharma Kumar|chapter=Population (1757\u20131947)|ref= harv}}\n*{{citation |last=Vishwanath |first=L. S.|title=Sex-Selective Abortion in India: Gender, Society and New Reproductive Technologies |year=2007 |publisher=SAGE |isbn=978-0-76193-539-1 |editor-first=Tulsi |editor-last=Patel |chapter=Female Infanticide, Property and the Colonial State |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UegqZBISwBYC}}\n* {{cite book|last=Winkler|first=Theodor H.|title=Women in an Insecure World|year=2005|publisher=Geneva Centre for the Democratic Control of Armed Forces|chapter-url=http://www.unicef.org/emerg/files/women_insecure_world.pdf|chapter=Slaughtering Eve The Hidden Gendercide|ref= harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |last1=Barlow |first1=Sally H. |last2=Clayton |first2=Claudia J. |editor-last=Hall |editor-first=Harold V. |title=Lethal Violence: A Sourcebook on Fatal Domestic, Acquaintance and Stranger Violence |year=1998 |publisher=CRC Press |isbn=978-0-8493-7003-8 |chapter=When Mothers Murder: Understanding Infanticide by Females |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9KXJoS2pQJMC}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Bhatnagar |first1=Rashmi Dube |first2=Renu |last2=Dube |first3=Reena |last3=Dube |title=Female Infanticide in India: A Feminist Cultural History |year=2005 |publisher=State University of New York Press |isbn=978-0-7914-6327-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kT0s8TXoffsC}}\n* {{cite news |last=Bunting |first=Madeleine |authorlink=Madeleine Bunting |title=India's missing women |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/poverty-matters/2011/jul/22/india-sex-selection-missing-women|accessdate=2015-05-26 |work=The Guardian |date=22 July 2011}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kannabiran |first=Kalpana |title=Writings on Human Rights, Law and Society in India: Combat Law Anthology 2002\u20132010 |year=2011 |publisher=Human Rights Law Network, India (Socio-Legal Information Centre) |isbn=978-81-89479-78-7 |editor-first=Harsh |editor-last=Dobhal |chapter=Gender Cleansing |quote=Female Foeticide and female infanticide satisfy four of the five criteria set out in the Genocide Convention |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CcbLvuT1jbkC}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Meyer |first1=Cheryl L. |last2=Oberman |first2=Michelle |title=Mothers Who Kill Their Children: Inside the Minds of Moms from Susan Smith to the \"Prom Mom\" |year=2001 |publisher=New York University Press |isbn=978-0-8147-5643-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0g6xYkMUrKkC}}\n* {{cite news|last=Krishnan|first=Murali|title=Female infanticide in India mocks claims of progress|url=http://www.dw.de/female-infanticide-in-india-mocks-claims-of-progress/a-15900828|newspaper=Deutsche Welle|date=20 March 2012|editor=Shamil Shams}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Nelson |first1=Dean |title=India 'most dangerous place in world to be born a girl' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/india/9054429/India-most-dangerous-place-in-world-to-be-born-a-girl.html |accessdate=2015-05-26 |publisher=The Daily Telegraph |date=1 February 2012}}\n* {{cite book |first=Brian K. |last=Pennington |year=2005 |url=https://www.questia.com/read/120211438/was-hinduism-invented-britons-indians-and-colonial |title=Was Hinduism Invented?: Britons, Indians, and the Colonial Construction |publisher=Oxford University Press |via=[[Questia]] |url-access=subscription }}\n* {{cite book |last=Ramachandran |first=Nira |title=Persisting Undernutrition in India: Causes, Consequences and Possible Solutions |publisher=Springer |year=2014 | isbn=978-8-13221-831-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lvH2ngEACAAJ}}\n* {{cite book |last=Sadhak |first=H. |title=Pension Reform in India: The Unfinished Agenda |publisher=Sage Publications |year=2013 |isbn= 978-8-13211-649-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qN2GAwAAQBAJ}}\n* {{cite book | last=Smith | first=M | title=Homicide : a sourcebook of social research | publisher=Sage Publications | location=Thousand Oaks, Calif | year=1999 | isbn=978-0-7619-0765-7}}\n\n{{Social issues in India}}\n\n[[Category:Sex selection in India| ]]\n[[Category:Child abandonment]]\n[[Category:Infanticide|India]]\n[[Category:Childhood in India]]\n", "name_user": "Bishmg", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFurther reading)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Female_infanticide_in_India"}
{"title_page": "Professional ethics", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Professional Ethics (journal)}}\n[[File:HippocraticOath.jpg|thumb|200px|A 12th-century [[Byzantine empire|Byzantine]] manuscript of the [[Hippocratic oath]].]]\n'''Professional ethics'''  encompass the personal and corporate standards of behavior expected by [[professional]]s.<ref>[http://www.architecture.com/Files/RIBAProfessionalServices/ProfessionalConduct/Constitution/CodeOfConduct/2005RIBACodeOfProfessionalConduct.pdf Royal Institute of British Architects - Code of professional conduct] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618044002/http://www.architecture.com/Files/RIBAProfessionalServices/ProfessionalConduct/Constitution/CodeOfConduct/2005RIBACodeOfProfessionalConduct.pdf |date=2013-06-18 }}</ref>\n\nThe word professionalism originally applied to vows of a religious order. By at least the year 1675, the term had seen secular application and was applied to the three learned professions: [[Divinity]], [[Law]], and [[Medicine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.co.wise.tx.us/constable/Downloads/Professionalism%20and%20Ethics.pdf|title = Professionalism and Ethics|date = |access-date = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>  The term professionalism was also used for the military profession around this same time.\n\nProfessionals and those working in acknowledged professions exercise specialist knowledge and skill. How the use of this knowledge should be governed when providing a service to the public can be considered a moral issue and is termed professional ethics.<ref>Ruth Chadwick (1998). Professional Ethics. In E. Craig (Ed.), Routledge Encyclopedia of Philosophy. London: Routledge. Retrieved October 20, 2006, from https://www.rep.routledge.com/articles/thematic/professional-ethics/v-1</ref>\n\nIt is capable of making judgments, applying their skills, and reaching informed decisions in situations that the general public cannot because they have not attained the necessary knowledge and skills.<ref>Caroline Whitbeck, \"Ethics in Engineering Practice and Research\" Cambridge University Press, 1998 page 40</ref> One of the earliest examples of professional ethics is the [[Hippocratic oath]] to which medical [[physician|doctors]] still adhere to this day.\n\n==Components==\nSome professional organizations may define their ethical approach in terms of a number of discrete components.<ref>[http://www.rics.org/site/download_feed.aspx?fileID=6309&fileExtension=PDF RICS- MAINTAINING PROFESSIONAL AND ETHICAL STANDARDS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111216090731/http://www.rics.org/site/download_feed.aspx?fileID=6309&fileExtension=PDF |date=2011-12-16 }}</ref> Typically these include [[Honesty]], [[Integrity]], [[Transparency (behavior)|Transparency]], [[Accountability]], [[Confidentiality]], [[Objectivity (journalism)|Objectivity]], [[Respect]], [[Legal|Obedience to the law]], and [[Loyalty]].\n\n==Implementation==\nMost professionals have internally enforced codes of practice that members of the profession must follow to prevent [[wikt: exploitation|exploitation]] of the client and to preserve the integrity and reputation of the profession. This is not only for the benefit of the client but also for the benefit of those belonging to that profession. Disciplinary codes allow the profession to define a standard of conduct and ensure that individual practitioners meet this standard, by disciplining them from the professional body if they do not practice accordingly. This allows those professionals who act with a conscience to practice in the knowledge that they will not be undermined commercially by those who have fewer ethical qualms. It also maintains the public\u2019s trust in the profession, encouraging the public to continue seeking their services.\n\n===Internal regulation===\nIn cases where professional bodies regulate their own ethics, there are possibilities for such bodies to become self-serving and fail to follow their own ethical code when dealing with renegade members. This is particularly true of professions in which they have almost a complete monopoly on a particular area of knowledge. For example, until recently, the English courts deferred to the professional consensus on matters relating to their practice that lay outside case law and legislation.<ref>Margaret Brazier, \u2018\u2019Medicine, Patients and the Law\u2019\u2019, Penguin, 1987 page 147</ref>\n\n==Statutory regulation==\nIn many countries there is some statutory regulation of professional ethical standards such as the [[statutory body|statutory bodies]] that regulate [[nursing]] and [[midwife]]ry in England and Wales.<ref>[http://www.bristol-inquiry.org.uk/final_report/annex_a/chapter_4_15.htm The Bristol Royal Infirmary inquiry-Professional regulation - nursing: the UKCC ] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120729062133/http://www.bristol-inquiry.org.uk/final_report/annex_a/chapter_4_15.htm |date=2012-07-29 }}</ref> Failure to comply with these standards can thus become a matter for the courts.\n\n==Examples==\nFor example, a lay member of the public should not be held responsible for failing to act to save a [[car crash]] victim because they could not give an appropriate [[emergency treatment]]. Though, they are responsible for attempting to get help for the victim. This is because they do not have the relevant knowledge and experience. In contrast, a fully trained doctor (with the correct equipment) would be capable of making the correct [[diagnosis]] and carrying out appropriate procedures. Failure of a doctor to not help at all in such a situation would generally be regarded as [[negligent]] and [[unethical]]. Though, if a doctor helps and makes a mistake that is considered negligent and unethical, there could be [[wikt:egregious|egregious]] repercussions. An untrained person would only be considered to be negligent for failing to act if they did nothing at all to help and is protected by the [[Good Samaritan law|\"Good Samaritan\" laws]] if they unintentionally caused more damage and possible loss of life.\n\nA business may approach a professional engineer to certify the safety of a project which is not safe. While one engineer may refuse to certify the project on moral grounds, the business may find a less [https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/scrupulous scrupulous] engineer who will be prepared to certify the project for a [[bribe]], thus saving the business the expense of redesigning.<ref>Michael Davis, \u2018Thinking like an Engineer\u2019 in Philosophy and Public Affairs, 20.2 (1991) page 158</ref>\n\n===Separatism===\nOn a theoretical level, there is debate as to whether an ethical code for a profession should be consistent with the requirements of morality governing the public. Separatists argue that professions should be allowed to go beyond such confines when they judge it necessary. This is because they are trained to produce certain outcomes which may take moral precedence over other functions of society.<ref name=Gewirth>{{cite journal\n | last =Gewirth\n | first =Alan\n | title =Professional Ethics: The Separatist Thesis\n | journal =Ethics\n | volume =96\n | issue =2\n | pages =282\u2013300\n | date =Jan 1986\n | jstor =2381378\n | doi=10.1086/292747}}\n</ref>{{rp|282}} For example, it could be argued that a doctor may lie to a patient about the severity of his or her condition if there is reason to believe that telling the patient would cause so much distress that it would be [[detrimental]] to his or her health. This would be a disrespect of the patient's [[autonomy]], as it denies the patient information that could have a great impact on his or her life. This would generally be seen as morally wrong. However, if the end of improving and maintaining health is given a moral priority in society, then it may be justifiable to [https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/contravene contravene] other moral demands in order to meet this goal.<ref name=Gewirth/>{{rp|284}} Separatism is based on a relativist conception of morality that there can be different, equally valid, moral codes that apply to different sections of society and differences in codes between societies (see [[moral relativism]]). If [[moral universalism]] is ascribed to, then this would be inconsistent with the view that professions can have a different moral code, as the universalist holds that there is only one valid moral code for all.<ref name=Gewirth/>{{rp|285}}.\n\n==Student ethics==\nAs attending college after high school graduation becomes a standard in the lives of young people, [[colleges]] and [[universities]] are becoming more business-like in their expectations of the students.  Although people have differing opinions about if it is effective, surveys state that it is the overall goal of the university administrators.<ref>{{cite web|title=Are Colleges Preparing Students For The Workplace|url=http://www.thecollegesolution.com/are-colleges-preparing-students-for-the-workplace}}</ref>  Setting up a business-like atmosphere helps students get adjusted from a more relaxed nature, like high school, towards what will be expected of them in the business world upon graduating from College.\n\n===Codes of conduct===\nCodes of conduct, such as the St. Xavier Code of Conduct, are becoming more a staple in the academic lives of students.<ref>{{cite web|title=SXU Code of Conduct|url=http://www.sxu.edu/academics/resources/cie/conduct.asp|accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref> While some of these rules are based solely on academics others are more in depth than in previous years. Such as, detailing the level of respect expected towards staff and gambling.\n\nNot only do codes of conduct apply while attending the schools at home, but also while studying abroad. Schools also implement a code of conduct for international study abroad programs which carry over many of the same rules found in most student handbooks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Student Conduct|url=http://handbook.sxu.edu/Student/Code_Conduct/student_conduct.html}}</ref>\n\n== How to acquire Professional Attitude? ==\n[https://www.jinglingmoney.com/professional-attitude-in-business/ Professional attitude] reflects at how we treat people? People who are our: Employees, Colleagues, Bosses, Friends, Family, Partner etc. Professional attitude is an essential key element of running a [[business]] and it shows your [[business ethics]] to the world.\n\nProfessional attitude can be acquired in 5 simple steps i.e., By learning a discipline like martial arts, forming a reading habit like all millionaires do, by listening more, updating clothing and by looking elegant, and by releasing your stress through meditation.\n\nRelease performance pressure and keep participating in new outbound things. \n\n== Examples of professionals ==\n\n* Journalists.\n* Accountants.\n* Doctors.\n* Lawyers.\n* Managers.\n* Technicians.\n* HR experts.\n* Psychologists.\n* Businessmen.\n* Bloggers (like us).\n* Brewers.\n* Scientists.\n\nAnd so on. These are some of the examples of professionals which are commonly found around the globe.\n\n''A businessman can be a professional, but a professional cannot be a businessman.''\n\n==See also==\n{{col div|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Business ethics]]\n* [[Deontological ethics]]\n* [[Ethical code]]\n* [[Ethics]]\n* [[Engineering ethics]]\n* [[Legal ethics]]\n* [[Medical ethics]]\n* [[Nursing ethics]]\n* [[Outline of ethics]]\n* [[Professional]]\n* [[Professional abuse]]\n* [[Professional boundaries]]\n* [[Professional negligence in English Law]]\n* [[Professional responsibility]]\n* [[Virtue ethics]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n==Further reading==\n{{Wikibooks|Professionalism}}\n* [http://changingminds.org/explanations/values/values_morals_ethics.htm Values, morals, and ethics. Retrieved August 16, 2009,]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060716001602/http://www.asaecenter.org/PublicationsResources/articledetail.cfm?ItemNumber=13073 Joseph, J. (2007). Ethics in the Workplace. Retrieved August 16, 2009]\n* Walker, Evelyn, and Perry Deane Young (1986). ''A Killing Cure''. New York: H. Holt and Co. xiv, 338 p. ''N.B''.: Explanatory subtitle on book's dust cover: ''One Woman's True Account of Sexual and Drug Abuse and Near Death at the Hands of Her Psychiatrist''. Without ISBN\n\n{{Ethics}}\n\n[[Category:Professional ethics| ]]\n[[Category:Ethics]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Professional Ethics (journal)}}\n[[File:HippocraticOath.jpg|thumb|200px|A 12th-century [[Byzantine empire|Byzantine]] manuscript of the [[Hippocratic oath]].]]\n'''Professional ethics'''  encompass the personal and corporate standards of behavior expected by [[professional]]s.<ref>[http://www.architecture.com/Files/RIBAProfessionalServices/ProfessionalConduct/Constitution/CodeOfConduct/2005RIBACodeOfProfessionalConduct.pdf Royal Institute of British Architects - Code of professional conduct] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618044002/http://www.architecture.com/Files/RIBAProfessionalServices/ProfessionalConduct/Constitution/CodeOfConduct/2005RIBACodeOfProfessionalConduct.pdf |date=2013-06-18 }}</ref>\n\nThe word professionalism originally applied to vows of a religious order. By at least the year 1675, the term had seen secular application and was applied to the three learned professions: [[Divinity]], [[Law]], and [[Medicine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.co.wise.tx.us/constable/Downloads/Professionalism%20and%20Ethics.pdf|title = Professionalism and Ethics|date = |access-date = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>  The term professionalism was also used for the military profession around this same time.\n\nProfessionals and those working in acknowledged professions exercise specialist knowledge and skill. How the use of this knowledge should be governed when providing a service to the public can be considered a moral issue and is termed professional ethics.<ref>Ruth Chadwick (1998). Professional Ethics. In E. Cra